section.p:
In this book, we've already seen two different concepts for multiplication. When we were working with the
distributive property (), we talked about multiplication representing groups
of things and used this example: 

	\begin{aligned}
		4 \cdot (2 \text{ apples} + 3 \text{ oranges} ) \amp = 8 \text{ apples} + 12 \text{ oranges} 
	\end{aligned}

We also talked about multiplication being represented as an area ():

